        <h3 class="hed">How The Ballpoint Pen Killed Cursive</h3>
    </a>
    <ul class="metadata">
        <li class="byline"><a href="/author/josh-giesbrecht/" title="Josh Giesbrecht">Josh Giesbrecht</a></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="article-content ">
        <p class="dek">Thicker ink, fewer smudges, and more strained hands: an <a href="http://objectsobjectsobjects.com/">Object Lesson</a></p>
        
        <div class="excerpt">
            <p>Recently, Bic launched a<a href="http://www.bicfightforyourwrite.com/"> </a><a href="http://www.bicfightforyourwrite.com/">campaign to &#x201C;save handwriting.&#x201D;</a> Named &#x201C;Fight for Your Write,&#x201D; it includes a pledge to &#x201C;encourage the act of handwriting&#x201D; in the pledge-taker&#x2019;s home and community, and emphasizes putting more of the company&#x2019;s ballpoints into classrooms.</p>&#13;
&#13;
<p>As a teacher, I couldn&#x2019;t help but wonder how anyone could think there&#x2019;s a shortage. I find ballpoint pens all over the place: on classroom floors, behind desks. Dozens of castaways collect in cups on every teacher&#x2019;s desk. They&#x2019;re so ubiquitous that the word &#x201C;ballpoint&#x201D; is rarely used; they&#x2019;re just &#x201C;pens.&#x201D; But despite its popularity, the ballpoint pen is relatively new in the history of handwriting, and its influence on popular handwriting is more complicated than the Bic campaign would imply.</p>&#13;
&#13;

        </div>
        
